Problem 1 — the dictionary is missing most TYPE designators
-----------------------------------------------------------

`type` returns a small set of designator symbols, but chapter 4 only has
entries for NIL, Symbol (SYM), ENAME, PICKSET, FILE. Missing at least:

  - INT     — integers
  - REAL    — reals
  - STR     — strings
  - LIST    — cons cells (see Problem 2)
  - SUBR    — built-in/internal subroutine (BricsCAD returns SUBR for
              built-ins AND for lambdas in the observed probe)
  - USUBR   — user-defined subroutine (clautolisp returns USUBR for a user
              lambda: `#<USUBR LAMBDA>` -> USUBR)
  - EXSUBR / EXRXSUBR — external (ADS / ObjectARX) subroutines
  - PAGETB  — function paging table
  - VLA-OBJECT, SAFEARRAY, VARIANT — ActiveX/automation values

This is non-exhaustive. The designator set differs per host (e.g. SUBR vs
USUBR for user functions — see the cross-vendor note below), so the
authoritative list must be obtained by *probing*: run `type` over the
return values of as many AutoCAD and BricsCAD functions as practical and
collect every distinct designator. Worked evidence from the reporter:

  alfe --bricscad: (function type) -> type SUBR ; a user lambda -> SUBR
  clautolisp:      a user lambda   -> #<USUBR LAMBDA> -> type USUBR

So SUBR-vs-USUBR for user functions is itself a cross-vendor divergence
worth a Compatibility note on those entries.

Scope for Problem 1:
  - Add a Type Entry for each designator `type` can return, in the same
    template as the existing entries (Name = the exact designator token,
    Class, Description, Representation, Valid Operations, Availability,
    Source Notes).
  - Normalize the existing Symbol entry to the designator token SYM (keep
    "Symbol" as the prose name) so the dictionary is keyed by what `type`
    actually returns.
  - Record the host divergence for the function designators (SUBR /
    USUBR / EXSUBR / EXRXSUBR) — which host returns which for built-ins
    vs user functions vs ADS/ARX externals.
  - Probe both hosts; cite the `type` reference page's documented list as
    the starting catalogue and mark any designator seen in a probe but not
    in the docs (and vice-versa).

Problem 2 — LIST is the set of CONS cells only; it excludes NIL
---------------------------------------------------------------

The `LIST` designator covers cons cells (including dotted/improper pairs)
and does NOT include the empty list. Evidence:

  (type '(a . d)) ==> LIST
  (type 'nil)     ==> nil
  (type '())      ==> nil

So `(type X)` returns `LIST` iff X is a cons; for the empty list it
returns `nil`, not `LIST`. This must be stated explicitly, because it is
easy to conflate with the `listp` predicate, which returns T for BOTH
conses AND nil. The two notions diverge:

  - `listp` true set  = conses ∪ {nil}
  - `LIST` type set   = conses only

The current NIL entry (draft.org:1845-1846) lists "LIST" under Related
Types and says "nil is also the empty list" / "listp returns T for nil",
which is correct for `listp` but must NOT be read as "nil has type LIST".

Scope for Problem 2:
  - Add a LIST Type Entry stating: type set = cons cells (proper and
    dotted/improper); empty list is NOT of type LIST.
  - Add a normative note contrasting the `LIST` designator with the
    `listp` predicate (conses-only vs conses∪{nil}).
  - Adjust the NIL entry's "Related Types: LIST" so it does not imply nil
    is of type LIST; point instead at the listp-vs-LIST distinction.

Problem 3 — NIL behaves as bottom (⊥), not as a symbol
------------------------------------------------------

The NIL entry (draft.org:1838) already says `(type nil)` returns `nil`
(not a `NIL`/`SYM` designator) and that nil is the false value. It is
worth adding the unifying interpretation: in AutoLISP `nil` serves as
*bottom* (⊥), and that single reading explains the otherwise-odd facts:

  (type nil)    ==> nil        ; not SYM, not a distinct NIL designator
  (boundp 'nil) ==> nil
  (not (eq 'sym (type 'nil)))  ; the type of nil is NOT the symbol SYM

Argument to record: if `nil` were an ordinary symbol that evaluates to
`nil`, then `(boundp 'nil)` returning `nil` would be inconsistent (a
self-evaluating bound symbol). Reading `nil` as ⊥ makes the whole family
coherent — `(quote ⊥) ==> ⊥`, `(boundp ⊥) ==> ⊥`, `(type ⊥) ==> ⊥` —
every operation on bottom yields bottom. The "type NIL contains NIL"
phrasing (a singleton bottom type whose sole inhabitant prints as nil) is
the dual view.

Scope for Problem 3:
  - Add a Notes/Discussion subsection to the NIL entry presenting the ⊥
    interpretation as the rationale for the `type`/`boundp`/`eq` results,
    keeping the existing normative statements intact.
  - Keep it explicitly non-collapsible to Common Lisp symbol/type behaviour
    (the entry already warns against the CL `nil` type model — reinforce
    with the ⊥ framing).
  - Verify `(boundp 'nil)` and `(not (eq 'sym (type 'nil)))` on both hosts
    and cite, so the ⊥ reading is evidence-backed, not just argued.
  - Note the comparison predicates as another manifestation of ⊥
    propagation: `=` `/=` `<` `<=` `>` `>=` signal a type error on
    incompatible NON-nil types but return `nil` (not an error) when an
    argument is `nil` — e.g. `(< 1 nil) -> nil`, `(< "abc" nil) -> nil`.
    Keep this consistent with
    issues/open/autolisp-spec-comparison-operators-chapter-placement.issue.

Out of scope
------------

- Host object ontology details (ENAME/PICKSET/VLA-OBJECT internals) beyond
  giving each a dictionary entry — chapters 16/17/20 own the deep
  semantics.
- clautolisp's own printer reprs (`#<USUBR LAMBDA>` etc.) — relevant only
  as probe evidence for which designator a value carries.

Definition of done
-------------------

- Chapter 4 has a Type Entry for every designator `type` can return,
  obtained from the `type` reference plus an AutoCAD/BricsCAD probe, with
  cross-vendor divergences (esp. SUBR/USUBR) noted.
- A LIST entry states conses-only and a normative note distinguishes the
  `LIST` type from the `listp` predicate; the NIL entry no longer implies
  nil is of type LIST.
- The NIL entry documents the ⊥ interpretation as rationale for
  type/boundp/eq, backed by probed evidence.
- build/org regenerates cleanly from the draft.org source.
